To enable file and image transfer in your WebSocket server, you will need to modify the existing code to handle binary data. The "nodejs-websocket" library you're using might not directly support binary data out of the box, so you might need to switch to another library like `ws`.

Here's how you can implement a basic WebSocket server using the `ws` library that can handle both text and binary messages. Please note that this example assumes you have installed the `ws` library using `npm install ws`.

```js
const WebSocket = require('ws');
const fs = require('fs');

const server = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 3000 });

server.on('connection', function (ws) {
    console.log('New connection established.');

    ws.on('message', function (message) {
        if (typeof message === 'string') {
            // Handle text message
            console.log('Received text:', message);
            broadcast(message);
        } else if (message instanceof Buffer) {
            // Handle binary data
            console.log('Received binary data');
            // Here you can decide to save the file, for example.
            // This simple example will just broadcast the data back to all clients.
            broadcastBinary(message);
        }
    });

    ws.on('close', function () {
        console.log('Connection closed.');
    });

    ws.on('error', function (err) {
        console.error('WebSocket error:', err);
    });
});

function broadcast(message) {
    server.clients.forEach(function each(client) {
        if (client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
            client.send(message);
        }
    });
}

function broadcastBinary(data) {
    server.clients.forEach(function each(client) {
        if (client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
            client.send(data);
        }
    });
}

console.log('WebSocket server is running on ws://localhost:3000');
```

This server code handles both text and binary messages by distinguishing between them based on the type of the `message` object received in the `message` event listener. You can extend the `broadcastBinary` function to implement custom logic for handling file transfers, like saving files to disk instead of simply broadcasting them.

The client-side `socket.onmessage` event handling for binary data is already embedded in your HTML/Javascript code. However, make sure to define `socket.onmessage` only once and manage both text and binary data within the same handler.

Lastly, you should be aware that transferring files using WebSockets can be tricky for large files because WebSockets are not specifically designed for file transfers. You might need to implement mechanisms for splitting large files into chunks, sending them over multiple messages, and reassembling them on the client-side. For handling large file transfers, consider using dedicated file transfer protocols or services that are designed for such tasks.

The error message "Uncaught TypeError: Cannot set properties of undefined (setting 'onmessage')" suggests that you are attempting to assign an `'onmessage'` event handler to the `socket` when the `socket` variable itself is not properly initialized. This can happen if you are setting the `socket.onmessage` outside of a function scope where the `socket` variable is defined, or if the `socket` has not yet been assigned with a `WebSocket` object.

This is the line that's throwing the error, based on your error message:

```javascript
socket.onmessage = function (event) {
// ...
};
```

The error may occur if this code is running before the `WebSocket` has been instantiated. Here's how you can fix the issue:

1. Make sure the `socket` variable is not undefined when you assign the `onmessage` event handler.
2. In your code, the `onmessage` event handler should be set after initializing the `WebSocket` and within the function scope or after the `socket` variable has been given a value.
3. Additionally, make sure you are not assigning `socket.onmessage` more than once before the `socket` initialization, or do a check to ensure `socket` is not undefined before setting up the handler. 

For example:

```javascript
var socket;

function A() {
    // Initialization of socket and other operations
    socket = new WebSocket("ws://38.46.30.148:3000");

    // Now it's safe to set the event listeners
    socket.onopen = function (event) {
        // ...
    };
    socket.onmessage = function (event) {
        // ...
    };
    socket.onclose = function (event) {
        // ...
    };

    // Rest of your code...
}

// Further down in your code, do not set socket.onmessage again unless 
// we're sure socket is not undefined and is a WebSocket instance.

// ...
```

Make sure that you only set the `onmessage` property after the `socket` has been created with `new WebSocket`.

If you must define the `socket.onmessage` outside of the `A()` function, you can do so after checking for the `socket`'s existence and ensuring that `socket.readyState` is `WebSocket.OPEN`. However, this should really be occurring after you've called `A()` and the `socket` connection has been established. 

To prevent the error, you can also initialize your `socket` variable at the top of your script as `null` and then check if it's not null before setting properties like `onmessage`:

```javascript
var socket = null;

// Later in your code, when you're ready to set up the WebSocket:
if (socket !== null && socket.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
    socket.onmessage = function(event) {
        // Your event handling logic here
    };
}
```
Ensure you make such assignments after the `socket` has been instantiated by invoking the `A()` function or the part of your code where you establish the WebSocket connection.

